_As a foreword, the exact same code works just fine in XNA, but Monogame throws an exception.  This likely requires someone familiar with the Monogame rendering pipeline._

During the Draw section of my game, there's a ShadowmapResolver that renders out a texture that is the final calculated light pattern from a given light.  It's receiving an exception when rendering from what is essentially `EffectPass.Apply()` complaining that from somewhere within Mono theres an attempted cast from `int32[]` to `Single[]`.  Here's my code that calls it:

<!-- language: c# -->

```
private void ExecuteTechnique(Texture2D source, RenderTarget2D destination,
                              string techniqueName, Texture2D shadowMap)
{
    graphicsDevice.SetRenderTarget(destination);
    graphicsDevice.Clear(Color.Transparent);

    resolveShadowsEffect.Parameters["renderTargetSizeX"].SetValue((float)baseSizeX);
    resolveShadowsEffect.Parameters["renderTargetSizeY"].SetValue((float)baseSizeY);

    if (source != null)
        resolveShadowsEffect.Parameters["InputTexture"].SetValue(source);
    if (shadowMap != null)
        resolveShadowsEffect.Parameters["ShadowMapTexture"].SetValue(shadowMap);

    resolveShadowsEffect.CurrentTechnique = resolveShadowsEffect
        .Techniques[techniqueName];

    try
    {
        foreach (EffectPass pass in resolveShadowsEffect.CurrentTechnique.Passes)
        {
            pass.Apply(); // <--- InvalidCastException re-enters my program here
            quadRender.Render(Vector2.One * -1, Vector2.One);
        }
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        Util.Log(LogManager.LogLevel.Critical, ex.Message);
    }
    graphicsDevice.SetRenderTarget(null);
}
```

And here is the stacktrace:

```
at Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Graphics.ConstantBuffer.SetData(Int32 offset, Int32 rows, Int32 columns, Object data)
   at Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Graphics.ConstantBuffer.SetParameter(Int32 offset, EffectParameter param)
   at Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Graphics.ConstantBuffer.Update(EffectParameterCollection parameters)
   at Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Graphics.EffectPass.Apply()
   at JASG.ShadowmapResolver.ExecuteTechnique(Texture2D source, RenderTarget2D destination, String techniqueName, Texture2D shadowMap) in C:\Users\[snip]\dropbox\Projects\JASG2\JASG\JASG\Rendering\ShadowmapResolver.cs:line 253
```

So it would appear that one of the parameters of my shader which I am trying to set is confusing monogame somehow, but I don't see what it could be.  I'm pushing floats, not int arrays.  I even tried changing the `RenderTarget2D.SurfaceFormat` from Color to Single for all my targets and textures, still gives the exact same error.

Outside of the function I gave, in a broader scope, there are no other parameters being set since another `EffectPass.Apply`.  There are multiple other effects that render _without error_ before this one.

In case it helps, here's the source for the MonoGame Framework regarding `ConstantBuffer.SetData()`

<!-- language: c# -->

```
private void SetData(int offset, int rows, int columns, object data)
{
    // Shader registers are always 4 bytes and all the
    // incoming data objects should be 4 bytes per element.
    const int elementSize = 4;
    const int rowSize = elementSize * 4;

    // Take care of a single element.
    if (rows == 1 && columns == 1)
    {
        // EffectParameter stores all values in arrays by default.             
        if (data is Array)
            Buffer.BlockCopy(data as Array, 0, _buffer, offset, elementSize);
        else
        {
            // TODO: When we eventually expose the internal Shader 
            // API then we will need to deal with non-array elements.
            throw new NotImplementedException();   
        }
    }

    // Take care of the single copy case!
    else if (rows == 1 || (rows == 4 && columns == 4))
        Buffer.BlockCopy(data as Array, 0, _buffer, offset, rows*columns*elementSize);
    else
    {
        var source = data as Array;

        var stride = (columns*elementSize);
        for (var y = 0; y < rows; y++)
            Buffer.BlockCopy(source, stride*y, _buffer, offset + (rowSize*y), 
                             columns*elementSize);
    }
}
```

Is this some sort of marshaling problem?  Thanks for your time!

Edit: P.S.: The exception is an `InvalidCastException` and not a `NotImplementedException`.

If a player receives a phone call while playing a MonoGame game, when they return from the call (after hanging up or ignoring the call), MonoGame's OpenAL context seems to be broken. After the interruption ends, **sound effect instances no longer play anymore**. The only way to restore sound is to completely terminate the iOS app and restart it.

To solve this, it looks like we need to catch the interruption and set the OpenAL context to NULL, and then, when the interruption ends, reset the OpenAL context to its original value. From [Apple's docs](https://developer.apple.com/library/ios/documentation/Audio/Conceptual/AudioSessionProgrammingGuide/HandlingAudioInterruptions/HandlingAudioInterruptions.html):

> When using OpenAL for audio playback, implement an interruption listener callback function, as you do when using Audio Queue Services. However, your interruption code must additionally manage the OpenAL context. Upon interruption, set the OpenAL context to NULL. After the interruption ends, set the context to its prior state.

I've included some sample code below to help reproduce the issue. It creates a new `SoundEffectInstance` and plays it repeatedly every 2 seconds. If you open this app on an iPhone and then call that phone ([Gmail Chat's phone call tool](http://www.google.com/chat/voice/) is a great way to test this), the OpenAL session will be interrupted and when you return to the app the sound effect no longer plays.

I should also note that iOS interruptions are not limited to phone calls either; FaceTime calls also produce interruptions, and even text messages, alarms, and other modal alerts can cause interruptions on earlier versions of iOS. So this seems like a pretty critical bug to fix.

I have a fair amount of experience with the iOS sound notification/interruption API, but I'm very new to the MonoGame codebase, so I don't feel completely comfortable trying to hack the solution in place. Is there a resident "MonoGame sound expert"? I would love to collaborate with someone here to cobble together a solution and squash this bug.

Here's the sample code for reproducing this issue. (Note: You'll have to replace the `Content/sound.wav` file referenced below with whatever sound effect file you're using.)

``` C#
public class Game1 : Game
{
    GraphicsDeviceManager graphics;
    SoundEffectInstance soundEffectInstance;

    TimeSpan soundMax = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);
    TimeSpan soundElapsed = TimeSpan.Zero;

    public Game1 ()
    {
        graphics = new GraphicsDeviceManager (this);

        Content.RootDirectory = "Content";

        graphics.IsFullScreen = true;
        graphics.SupportedOrientations = DisplayOrientation.Portrait;
    }

    protected override void Initialize ()
    {
        base.Initialize ();
    }

    protected override void LoadContent ()
    {
        soundEffectInstance = new SoundEffect(
            File.ReadAllBytes("Content/sound.wav"), 41000, AudioChannels.Mono
        ).CreateInstance();
    }

    protected override void Update (GameTime gameTime)
    {
        soundElapsed += gameTime.ElapsedGameTime;
        if (soundElapsed >= soundMax)
        {
            soundElapsed = TimeSpan.Zero;
            soundEffectInstance.Play ();
        }

        base.Update (gameTime);
    }

    protected override void Draw (GameTime gameTime)
    {
        graphics.GraphicsDevice.Clear (Color.CornflowerBlue);
        base.Draw (gameTime);
    }
}
```

**The problem**
If the window border is visible, the cursor drifts on the y coordinate to the bottom. If the borders are not visible, the cursor is not internally moved to the requested position.

**Local information**
This was tested on Ubuntu 12.04 x86 with gnome 3.4.2.1, on a MSI gx660r (a notebook with an ATI HD5870 video card).

**To reproduce**
Run the following code. Click to set the mouse on the requested position.

``` c#
using System;
using Microsoft.Xna.Framework;
using Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Graphics;
using Microsoft.Xna.Framework.Input;

namespace MouseTest {
    public class Game1 : Game {
        GraphicsDeviceManager graphics;
        SpriteBatch spriteBatch;
        private Texture2D _cursor;
        private Vector2 cursorPos;

        public Game1 () {
            graphics = new GraphicsDeviceManager (this);
            Content.RootDirectory = "Content";
            graphics.IsFullScreen = false;      
            graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 640;
            graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 480;
            //Window.IsBorderless = true;
            IsMouseVisible = false;
        }

        protected override void LoadContent () {
            spriteBatch = new SpriteBatch (GraphicsDevice);
            _cursor = Content.Load<Texture2D>("cursor3");
        }

        protected override void Update (GameTime gameTime) {
            KeyboardState _kbs = Keyboard.GetState ();
            if (_kbs.IsKeyDown (Keys.Escape)) {
                Exit ();
            }

            MouseState _mouseState = Mouse.GetState ();
            if (_mouseState.LeftButton == ButtonState.Pressed) {
                Mouse.SetPosition (graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth / 2, graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight / 2 - 1);
            }
            _mouseState = Mouse.GetState ();
            cursorPos = new Vector2 (_mouseState.X, _mouseState.Y);

            base.Update (gameTime);
        }

        protected override void Draw (GameTime gameTime) {
            graphics.GraphicsDevice.Clear (Color.CornflowerBlue);

            // Draws cursor
            spriteBatch.Begin();
            spriteBatch.Draw(_cursor, cursorPos, Color.White);
            spriteBatch.End();

            base.Draw (gameTime);
        }
    }
}
```

**Solution**
This is a two step solution issue. When the cursor is hidden, it seems that OpenTK's OpenTK.Input.Mouse.SetPosition expects the coordinates to be specified as an offset with respect to the previous mouse position (which must be translated to the center of the screen). This can be fixed in Input/Mouse.cs.

The second issue is that the cursor centering on OpenTK is made with respect to the whole window (including its borders), which means it cannot be computed as (width/2, height/2), and depends on the windowing system. This needs to be fixed in OpenTK, on Platform/X11/X11GLNative.cs.

I'll be submitting patches for these issues shortly.

